.TH "TEMPORAL.DURATION.SUBTRACT" "3JS" "December 8, 2025" "JavaScript" "JavaScript Reference Manual"
.SH NAME
Temporal.Duration.subtract \- Temporal.Duration.prototype.subtract()
.SH SYNOPSIS
The \f[B]\f[CB]subtract()\f[B]\f[R] method of
\f[CR]Temporal.Duration\f[R] instances returns a new
\f[CR]Temporal.Duration\f[R] object with the difference between this
duration and a given duration.
It is equivalent to adding the negated value of the other duration.
.SH SYNTAX
.IP
.EX
subtract(other)
.EE
.SS Parameters
.TP
\f[B]other\f[R]
A string, an object, or a \f[CR]Temporal.Duration\f[R] instance
representing a duration to add to this duration.
It is converted to a \f[CR]Temporal.Duration\f[R] object using the same
algorithm as \f[CR]Temporal.Duration.from()\f[R].
.SS Return value
A new \f[CR]Temporal.Duration\f[R] object representing the difference of
this duration and \f[CR]other\f[R].
.SS Exceptions
.TP
\f[B]RangeError\f[R]
Thrown in one of the following cases:
.RS
.IP \(bu 2
Either \f[CR]this\f[R] or \f[CR]other\f[R] is a calendar duration (it
has a non\-zero \f[CR]years\f[R], \f[CR]months\f[R], or
\f[CR]weeks\f[R]), because calendar durations are ambiguous without a
calendar and time reference.
.IP \(bu 2
The difference of \f[CR]this\f[R] and \f[CR]other\f[R] overflows the
maximum or underflows the minimum representable duration, which is
±2\(ha53 seconds.
.RE
.SH EXAMPLES
.SS Using subtract()
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] d1 = Temporal.Duration.from({ hours: 1, minutes: 30 });
\f[B]const\f[R] d2 = Temporal.Duration.from({ hours: \-1, minutes: \-20 });

\f[B]const\f[R] d3 = d1.subtract(d2);
console.log(d3.toString()); \f[I]// \(dqPT2H50M\(dq\f[R]
.EE
.PP
For more examples and caveats, see the \f[CR]add()\f[R] method.
.SH SEE ALSO
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]Temporal.Duration\f[R]
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]Temporal.Duration.prototype.add()\f[R]
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]Temporal.Duration.prototype.negated()\f[R]
